Over the years, a considerable number of prominent Canadians achieved membership in the [Privy Council of the United Kingdom](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom), thereby earning the right to use the "Right Honourable" style. This was often a recognition of their distinguished services while stationed in Britain, such as acting as envoys to London, or their critical roles as members of the [Imperial War Cabinet](/Imperial_War_Cabinet), or simply due to their significant prominence within the [Canadian Cabinet](/Canadian_Cabinet). This historical trajectory meant that all but three of Canada's early prime ministers—[Alexander Mackenzie](/Alexander_Mackenzie_(politician)), [John Abbott](/John_Abbott), and [Mackenzie Bowell](/Mackenzie_Bowell)—who served before the style became routinely applied domestically, eventually acquired this title.

### New Zealand

Previously, in [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), it was customary for the [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_New_Zealand) and certain other senior cabinet ministers to be appointed to the [Privy Council of the United Kingdom](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom), automatically entitling them to be styled "Right Honourable." This was a direct link to the imperial tradition.

However, [Helen Clark](/Helen_Clark), during her tenure as [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_New_Zealand) from 1999 to 2008, chose not to recommend any new appointments of New Zealanders to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom). Her successor, [John Key](/John_Key), continued this departure from tradition, announcing in 2009 his decision to refrain from making any further recommendations to [the Crown](/The_Crown) for appointments to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom). This effectively signaled the end of New Zealand's direct participation in the British [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom) system.

In a move to establish a distinctly New Zealand-centric system of honorifics, the [Queen of New Zealand](/Monarchy_of_New_Zealand) formally announced in August 2010 that, with immediate effect, individuals holding, or subsequently appointed to, the following high offices would be awarded the style "Right Honourable" for life:

*   The [Governor-General of New Zealand](/Governor-General_of_New_Zealand)
*   The [Prime Minister of New Zealand](/Prime_Minister_of_New_Zealand)
*   The [Chief Justice of New Zealand](/Chief_Justice_of_New_Zealand)
*   The [Speaker of the New Zealand House of Representatives](/Speaker_of_the_New_Zealand_House_of_Representatives)

This change was a direct response to the cessation of appointments of New Zealanders to the [Privy Council of the United Kingdom](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom). Despite its significance, the immediate practical impact of this change was somewhat limited, as all but two of the individuals holding or having previously held these newly designated offices had already been appointed to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom) under the old system. The exceptions were former governor-generals Sir [Paul Reeves](/Paul_Reeves), Dame [Catherine Tizard](/Catherine_Tizard) and Dame [Silvia Cartwright], and former speakers Sir [Kerry Burke](/Kerry_Burke), Sir [Robin Gray](/Robin_Gray_(New_Zealand_politician)), Sir [Peter Tapsell](/Peter_Tapsell_(New_Zealand_politician)), Sir [Doug Kidd](/Doug_Kidd) and [Margaret Wilson](/Margaret_Wilson), who would now benefit from the new domestic entitlement.

