### Africa

In various African nations, the "Right Honourable" style has found its place, often reflecting a colonial legacy intertwined with post-independence political structures. During its periods of existence, the post of [Prime Minister of Kenya](/Prime_Minister_of_Kenya) was styled "Right Honourable." In post-independence Kenya, two individuals have been granted this distinction. The nation's founding president, [Jomo Kenyatta](/Jomo_Kenyatta), who served as Kenya's inaugural prime minister, was one. The other is [Raila Amolo Odinga](/Raila_Amolo_Odinga), who held the country's second prime ministerial office between 2008 and 2013. [Raila Odinga](/Raila_Odinga), affectionately known as Baba (a political father figure and an enigma in his own right), is widely recognized as a towering icon in Africa, celebrated for his fervent [Pan-Africanism](/Pan-Africanism) and his relentless advocacy for good governance. Beyond Kenya, the [prime ministers of Namibia](/Prime_Minister_of_Namibia) and [Uganda](/Prime_Minister_of_Uganda) are both currently styled with the same honorific. Furthermore, in [Uganda](/Uganda), both the speaker and deputy speaker of the [Parliament of Uganda](/Parliament_of_Uganda) are also accorded this style, extending the honour beyond the executive branch.

### Caribbean

Across the vibrant nations of the Caribbean, the "Right Honourable" style continues to denote high office. The prime ministers of [Barbados](/Barbados), [Grenada](/Grenada), [Saint Lucia](/Saint_Lucia), [Saint Vincent and the Grenadines](/Saint_Vincent_and_the_Grenadines), and [Trinidad and Tobago](/Trinidad_and_Tobago) are all formally styled "Right Honourable." Even the [West Indies Federation prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_the_West_Indies_Federation), during that office's relatively brief existence, was similarly styled, underscoring its widespread adoption in the region.

### Malaysia

In [Malaysia](/Malaysia), the application of the "Right Honourable" style (translated into Malay as "Yang Amat Berhormat" for political figures and "Yang Amat Arif" for judges) is reserved for a select few at both federal and state levels. Federally, only the [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Malaysia), his or her [deputy](/Deputy_Prime_Minister_of_Malaysia), four specific judges of the [Federal Court of Malaysia](/Federal_Court_of_Malaysia), and [Members of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)) who bear the personal title of [Tun](/Malay_styles_and_titles) are styled as Right Honourable. The four specific judges include the Chief Justice, the President of the Court of Appeal, and the Chief Judges of the High Court in Malaya and the High Court in Sabah and Sarawak. At the state level, all the [Menteris Besar, Chief Ministers and Premier](/Heads_of_state_governments_of_Malaysia), along with their deputies, are also granted the "Right Honourable" style, highlighting their significant roles within the federated system.

### Nepal

In [Nepal](/Nepal), the honorific system is quite structured. The [president](/President_of_Nepal), [vice president](/Vice_President_of_Nepal), speaker of the House of Representatives, [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Nepal), and [chief justice](/Chief_Justice_of_Nepal) are all formally styled "Right Honourable" (in [Nepali](/Nepali_language): सम्माननीय, romanized: *Sammānanīya*). In contrast, ministers, members of parliament (encompassing both Lower and Upper Houses, as well as provincial parliaments), and chief ministers of provinces are simply styled "Honourable." This creates a clear, if sometimes humorously discussed in informal circles, differentiation between senior and less senior government dignitaries. The English rendition can also be seen as "The Rt. Hon’ble."

### South Korea

In [South Korea](/South_Korea), the nation's most senior officials are also recognized with a similar, if less frequently observed, honorific. The [President](/President_of_Korea), [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_South_Korea), [Speaker of the National Assembly](/Speaker_of_the_National_Assembly_of_South_Korea), and [Chief Justice](/Chief_Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_Korea) are all entitled to use the "Right Honourable" style, though its application in practice may vary.

### Spain

Within the Spanish [autonomous community](/Autonomous_communities_of_Spain) of [Catalonia](/Catalonia), a distinct usage of the "Right Honourable" style exists. Both the [president of the Generalitat de Catalunya](/President_of_the_Government_of_Catalonia) and the president of the [Parliament of Catalonia](/Parliament_of_Catalonia) are formally referred to as "the Right Honourable," underscoring the high regard for these regional leadership positions.

## Countries with rare or historic usage

### Australia

In [Australia](/Australia), the application of the "Right Honourable" style is more limited in contemporary use, primarily surviving in specific civic roles. The [lord mayors](/Lord_mayor) of [Adelaide](/Adelaide), [Brisbane](/Brisbane), [Hobart](/Hobart), [Melbourne](/Melbourne), [Perth](/Perth), and [Sydney](/Sydney) are entitled to be styled "Right Honourable" during their respective terms in office, a nod to British tradition within local government.

Historically, a more significant number of Australians were entitled to this style by virtue of their membership in the [Privy Council of the United Kingdom](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom). It is important to distinguish that appointment to the Australian equivalent of the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom), the [Federal Executive Council](/Federal_Executive_Council_(Australia)), does not confer the "Right Honourable" style. Typical appointees to the Imperial [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom) from Australia included senior politicians and judges at both state and federal levels. [Malcolm Fraser](/Malcolm_Fraser), in 1976, was the most recent prime minister to accept appointment to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom) and thus be styled "Right Honourable." Of his 21 predecessors, only four were *not* members of the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom): [Alfred Deakin](/Alfred_Deakin) (who declined the appointment), [Chris Watson](/Chris_Watson) (who was never offered it), [Arthur Fadden](/Arthur_Fadden) (who accepted only after leaving office), and [Gough Whitlam](/Gough_Whitlam) (who also declined). The last [Governor-General](/Governor_General_of_Canada) of Australia to be entitled to the style was [Sir Ninian Stephen](/Ninian_Stephen), whose term concluded in 1988. The last active politician to hold the entitlement was [Ian Sinclair](/Ian_Sinclair), who retired from public life in 1998. The few Australian recipients of British peerages were also, by extension, entitled to this style.

Present-day Australian governments have largely distanced themselves from recommending Australians for elevation to the peerage or appointment to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom). However, some current Australian citizens continue to hold hereditary peerages, such as [Malcolm Murray, 12th Earl of Dunmore](/Malcolm_Murray,_12th_Earl_of_Dunmore), thereby retaining the associated style.

